---
import DocsLayout from '../../layouts/DocsLayout.astro';
import CodeBlock from '../../components/CodeBlock.astro';

const toc = [
  { label: 'Welcome to AIRLab',     id: 'welcome' },
  { label: 'Getting Access',        id: 'access' },
  { label: 'Core Responsibilities', id: 'responsibilities' },
  { label: 'Storage Policy',        id: 'storage' },
  { label: 'Resource Booking',      id: 'booking' },
  { label: 'Key Rules at a Glance', id: 'rules' },
];
---

<DocsLayout title="Welcome & Onboarding" toc={toc}>

  <h1>Welcome & Onboarding</h1>

  <p>
    Welcome to the <strong>Artificial Intelligence and Robotics Lab (AIRLab)</strong> at
    Politecnico di Milano. This handbook is your starting point. Read it carefully before
    touching any shared resource — what seems like a minor oversight can disrupt experiments
    running for hours across the lab.
  </p>

  <div class="callout callout-info">
    <svg class="w-5 h-5 flex-shrink-0 mt-0.5 text-accent-500" fill="none" stroke="currentColor"
         stroke-width="2" viewBox="0 0 24 24">
      <circle cx="12" cy="12" r="10"/><line x1="12" y1="8" x2="12" y2="12"/>
      <line x1="12" y1="16" x2="12.01" y2="16"/>
    </svg>
    <p class="text-sm leading-relaxed">
      <strong>New member?</strong> The first thing to do is ask your co-supervisor for access
      credentials and the resource-booking link. Then come back here and read through the rest.
    </p>
  </div>

  <!-- ── Welcome ───────────────────────────────────────────────────────────── -->
  <h2 id="welcome">Welcome to AIRLab</h2>

  <p>
    AIRLab hosts shared GPU servers — powerful machines used simultaneously by many
    researchers and thesis students. Shared infrastructure is both a privilege and a
    responsibility. The guidelines in this handbook exist not to restrict you, but to
    ensure that everyone — including you — can work without friction.
  </p>

  <p>
    The lab's compute environment is built around four pillars:
  </p>

  <ul>
    <li><strong>Reproducibility</strong> — every experiment runs inside a Docker container, so results can be replicated by anyone, on any machine.</li>
    <li><strong>Fairness</strong> — compute resources (CPUs, GPUs) are booked in advance, not grabbed ad hoc.</li>
    <li><strong>Cleanliness</strong> — your home directory has a firm storage cap; large data lives on the NAS.</li>
    <li><strong>Documentation</strong> — code is versioned on Git with a clear README, so future lab members can build on your work.</li>
  </ul>

  <!-- ── Getting Access ────────────────────────────────────────────────────── -->
  <h2 id="access">Getting Access</h2>

  <p>
    Your co-supervisor will create a Linux account for you on Westworld (the main lab server).
    Your username follows the convention <code>firstname.lastname</code> (all lowercase).
    Once you have credentials, verify your login:
  </p>

  <CodeBlock
    lang="bash"
    filename="local machine"
    code={`ssh firstname.lastname@<westworld_ip>`}
  />

  <p>
    You will be prompted for a temporary password. Change it immediately on first login:
  </p>

  <CodeBlock
    lang="bash"
    filename="westworld"
    code={`passwd
# Enter current (temporary) password, then your new password twice.
# Use a strong passphrase — this account has access to lab GPUs.`}
  />

  <p>
    We strongly recommend switching to <strong>SSH key authentication</strong> to avoid
    typing passwords over the network. See the
    <a href="/docs/shell#ssh-keys">SSH Keys section</a> in the Shell guide for setup instructions.
  </p>

  <!-- ── Core Responsibilities ──────────────────────────────────────────────── -->
  <h2 id="responsibilities">Core Responsibilities</h2>

  <p>
    Every AIRLab member is expected to uphold the following practices from day one.
    Repeated violations may result in account suspension.
  </p>

  <table>
    <thead>
      <tr><th>Responsibility</th><th>What it means in practice</th></tr>
    </thead>
    <tbody>
      <tr>
        <td><strong>Use Docker for all experiments</strong></td>
        <td>Never install Python packages globally with <code>pip install</code>. All code runs inside a container built from your project's <code>Dockerfile</code>.</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td><strong>Book resources before using them</strong></td>
        <td>Reserve CPU cores and GPUs via the shared booking system before starting any experiment. Ask your co-supervisor for the link.</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td><strong>Respect storage limits</strong></td>
        <td>Your home directory (<code>~</code>) is capped at <strong>20 GB</strong>. Datasets and large files go in <code>~/datasets/private</code>, which is a symlink to the NAS.</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td><strong>Version your code on Git</strong></td>
        <td>All project code lives in a private GitHub repository with your co-supervisors added as members.</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td><strong>Document your work</strong></td>
        <td>Every project must have a <code>README.md</code> that a stranger could use to reproduce your results from scratch.</td>
      </tr>
    </tbody>
  </table>

  <!-- ── Storage Policy ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────── -->
  <h2 id="storage">Storage Policy</h2>

  <p>
    The home directory (<code>/home/firstname.lastname</code>) has a <strong>20 GB hard quota</strong>.
    Exceeding it will prevent you from saving files — including experiment outputs —
    which can corrupt a running job.
  </p>

  <p>
    The NAS (network-attached storage) is mounted for large data. Your personal NAS space
    is accessible via a symlink in your home directory:
  </p>

  <CodeBlock
    lang="bash"
    filename="westworld"
    code={`# Datasets and large files go here — NOT in ~/
~/datasets/private/

# Check how much home-directory space you are using
ncdu -x ~

# Quick disk usage summary (top-level directories only)
du -sh ~/* 2>/dev/null | sort -rh | head -20`}
  />

  <div class="callout callout-warning">
    <svg class="w-5 h-5 flex-shrink-0 mt-0.5 text-yellow-500" fill="none" stroke="currentColor"
         stroke-width="2" viewBox="0 0 24 24">
      <path d="M10.29 3.86L1.82 18a2 2 0 0 0 1.71 3h16.94a2 2 0 0 0 1.71-3L13.71 3.86a2 2 0 0 0-3.42 0z"/>
      <line x1="12" y1="9" x2="12" y2="13"/><line x1="12" y1="17" x2="12.01" y2="17"/>
    </svg>
    <div class="text-sm leading-relaxed">
      <strong>Common mistake:</strong> unzipping a large dataset directly into
      <code>~/</code> instead of <code>~/datasets/private/</code>.
      Always double-check your destination path before unpacking archives.
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- ── Resource Booking ────────────────────────────────────────────────────── -->
  <h2 id="booking">Resource Booking</h2>

  <p>
    All CPU cores and GPUs must be reserved before use. The booking system prevents two
    researchers from unknowingly competing for the same hardware and degrading each other's
    results.
  </p>

  <p>
    The booking interface is an internal tool — ask your co-supervisor for the URL and
    access credentials. When booking:
  </p>

  <ul>
    <li>Reserve only what your experiment actually needs. Booking 8 GPUs for a single-GPU job wastes resources for colleagues.</li>
    <li>Set a realistic end time. If your job finishes early, release the reservation.</li>
    <li>Check GPU availability with <code>nvidia-smi</code> before starting to confirm no one else is using your reserved slots.</li>
  </ul>

  <CodeBlock
    lang="bash"
    filename="westworld"
    code={`# See which GPUs are in use and how much memory is free
nvidia-smi

# Watch GPU utilisation live (updates every 2 seconds)
watch -n 2 nvidia-smi`}
  />

  <!-- ── Rules at a Glance ───────────────────────────────────────────────────── -->
  <h2 id="rules">Key Rules at a Glance</h2>

  <table>
    <thead>
      <tr><th>Do</th><th>Don't</th></tr>
    </thead>
    <tbody>
      <tr>
        <td>Run all experiments inside Docker containers</td>
        <td>Install packages globally with <code>pip</code>, <code>conda</code>, or <code>apt</code></td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td>Store datasets in <code>~/datasets/private/</code></td>
        <td>Fill your home directory with large files</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td>Book GPUs and CPUs before starting jobs</td>
        <td>Use unbooked resources, even briefly</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td>Keep a clean, documented Git repository</td>
        <td>Commit notebooks with large outputs, model weights, or datasets</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td>Use <code>tmux</code> to keep sessions alive after disconnecting</td>
        <td>Leave orphan processes running after your session ends</td>
      </tr>
    </tbody>
  </table>

  <p>
    If you are ever unsure whether something is allowed, ask your co-supervisor or a
    senior lab member. When in doubt, err on the side of caution — the shared
    infrastructure depends on mutual respect.
  </p>

</DocsLayout>
